text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text: @igrannapp from @nytimes: on a monday night in midtown #manhattan, a group of approximately 20 men were baring their #souls. “i’m angry that my health is deteriorating. i’m not ready to be an old man,” said jeff nichols who’s 70. ranging in age from 30 to 70, the men were gathered as part of the @themankindproject (mkp), a 33-year-old nonprofit with 24 chapters in the u.s. and 11 regions abroad. it focuses on things like men’s emotional well-being, drawing on elements like carl jung’s theories of the psyche, nonviolent communication, breath work and native american customs. men, who are less likely than women to seek out individual therapy, are increasingly looking for outlets in this fraught cultural moment of political acrimony, widespread economic instability and major societal reckoning over their behavior. at mkp, membership is at an all-time high and enrollment is up 8% over the last year, said boysen hodgson, the director of marketing and communications. “with time’s up now and #metoo, many men know they have to be more accountable,” boysen said. “a lot of them are saying, ‘i don’t want that to be me. i don’t want that to be how #men are seen in the world.’” @caseykelbaugh took this photo during an mkp weekly meeting in manhattan. visit the link in our profile to read more.

text:
sometimes i’d just like to read a book without being kneaded and drooled in. but sometimes it’s nice to be loved in a kitty cat way.
-
my therapist recommended some intense reading over the next month or so while we get into some aggressive “sexual assault survivor specific therapy”. it’s been incredibly eye opening to see just how much i’ve been affected.
-
i used to think that my traumas didn’t affect my day to day. i used to think i was surviving just fine and doing ok. but the last few sessions and starting this reading has really made me see how affected i am. but knowing what’s affected and why means that i now know what steps i need to take to make improvements. and i’m so stinking excited to make them.
.
.
.
#welcometomyjourney #metoo #sexualassaultsurvivor #ccasa #babysteps #makingimprovements #bitbybit #catsofinstagram #imsoexcitedtobemeagain

recordemos que no hace mucho un grupo de artistas peruanas denunciaron al violador de guillermo castrillón. a raíz del testimonio de eva bracamonte, se sumaron más denuncias contra este tipo. el modus operandi es similar, hombres 'reconocidos' en situación de poder e influencia, aprovechan su posición para violentar sexualmente a mujeres en círculos artísticos ( y no artísticos). y que no nos vaya a sorprender cuando salgan a defender a darthés y digan que no fue violación, que no nos sorprenda cuando cuestionen por qué la víctima no denunció antes y por qué usaba short, etc. habrán mil y una excusas para justificar al violador y culpar a la víctima. por eso creernos es el inicio de la desobediencia. yo te creo, hermana, yo te creo.
.
.
.
los úteros simbolizan la lucha de las mujeres esterilizadas en contra de su voluntad durante el gobierno de fujimori. ellas llevan esperando por justicia y reparación más de 20 años. 
ps: extraño a mis saqritas🌈

text:
finally, witches, after notallmen arsery and aaaalll sundry shitfuckery, here’s #womanup. this is the first stage: we need you! it won’t work without every witch contributing, so #toyourbrooms. 
what’s it all about? well, it goes back to this post from october:
https://www.facebook.com/229308590735867/posts/742534912746563/

in response to that, which went fucking crazy, our founder wrote a piece on @womensagenda (google that plus jennie hill). so. this made us think. about how women routinely don’t report, and #metoo featured only those who could. about how women want desperately to talk, yet have been unable. about how those who do speak are punished, ridiculed, ostracised and disbelieved. about how perps therefore go free and this leads directly to more violence and women’s and children’s deaths. and about how this has to change. stat. we can’t affect change unless we see the fucking problem. 
here’s where you come in. post reports of sexual misconduct to us, as it’s the only foolproof way to speak anonymously. here’s how: - write about your experiences (one or more) of sexual harassment, sexual assault and/or rape. describe what happened and the aftermath: what happened next, were you believed, and how did your life change? - write 10 words minimum and 400 maximum, preferably hand-written (type only if you can’t hand-write);
- use one side only of one sheet of paper/card; - put your name and/or contact deets on the reverse (they’ll remain anonymous but supply additional authenticity): if you can’t, participate but add an explanation of why you require absolute anonymity;
- don’t name perpetrators or clearly identify culpable situations/people; - post to p. o. box 451, daylesford, vic, 3460; and
-  like/comment/share this post to your networks. 
financial support is always optional, but there’s a heavy workload here, so consider including a small(ish) banknote with your letter, or contribute to patreon or paypal, or message for account deets (and for men not contributing, this plus sharing is your way to contribute): http://paypal.me/madwitches
https://www.patreon.com/madfuckingwitches

#womanup could be big. please get involved, we need you!

text:
there is a stereotype that’s often attached to mental illness: those struggling are seen as dangerous, unpredictable, incompetent, and at fault for a disorder they have no control over. that’s why it was shocking when on june 5th, kate spade was found dead from a confirmed suicide in her park avenue home. then, three days later, reports broke that anthony bourdain had taken his own life. from the outside looking in, neither spade, a legendary fashion designer and style icon, nor bourdain, a celebrated chef, author, television host, and noted #metoo ally, looked “the part.” they were both powerful, wealthy, successful, and beloved, with millions of adoring fans — fans who had no idea they were suffering.

but the truth is, mental illness does not discriminate. one in five adults in the united states has a mental health condition, and according to a report from the centers for disease control and prevention, the nation’s suicide rate is on the rise. from 1999 to 2016, the number of americans who died by suicide increased by 28 percent.

in the wake of spade and bourdain’s tragic deaths, countless people have taken to social media to share empathetic messages of love and support for anyone struggling with depression or suicidal thoughts, which is a hopeful reminder of how far the conversation around mental illness has come in the states.

but if #afriend has confided in you about their own severe depression or suicidal thoughts, it can be hard to know how to help. that is why hellogiggles asked experts to share tips for navigating this difficult subject. while there is no one right answer when it comes to mental health, these small things can make a big difference in the lives of your loved ones. #feelingalone

text:
on wednesdays, we read 📚
if you’re looking for a refreshingly candid perspective, this read is for you. roxane gay addresses all the complexities of the crossroads of modern feminism and the intersectionality of her own identities. key takeaways:
🌱“just because you survive something does not mean you are strong” here, gay uses this quote to address the notion that we attach strength to the survival of sexual assault solely based on survival.
🌱gay uses a lot of pop culture references to challenge how we think about identity and women’s politics 🌱”i believe women not just in the united states but throughout the world deserve equality and freedom but know i am in no position to tell women of other cultures what that equality and freedom should look like”

text:
when i found out that emily giffen has released her ninth book, “all we ever wanted,” i requested it at the library, got put on hold, and promptly forgot about it. last week i was pleasantly surprised learn that the book was available. around this time of the year the mood for something light and romantic strikes me and emily giffen is usually good for that. 📚 “all i ever wanted” opens from the  perspective of nina browning, the wife of a wealthy business man and mother to an 18 year old son, finch. while at a gala where nina and her husband are being honored for their contributions, nina learns that finch has shared a sexually inappropriate snapchat photo of a teen girl. tom volpe is the single, working class father of the teen girl featured in the photo. seeking justice for his daughter lyla, tom escalates the situation the dean of lyla and finch’s private school windsor academy. the story unfolds with point of view chapters for nina, tom, finch and lyla. 📚

the story was very engaging and incredibly timely given how much discussion there has been this year with the #metoo movement and cyber bullying. giffen ambitiously tackles several themes likes privilege, racism, infidelity, religion, rape, social media, etc. i felt that this novel was a bit outside of her wheelhouse and while i enjoyed reading it, i did wish giffen didn’t leave out the romance in favor of all of the aforementioned topics.📚 rating: ⭐️⭐️⭐️ #bookstagram #bookreview #2018reads #goodreads
name: Donda B. Reading

text:
this.every.day ❤️.
-
its the most wonderful time of the year ❤️ but it unfortunately leaves us feeling maxed out!  i am a planning queen👸🏼 (yes i gave myself a lil pat on the back 😜) but still feel the intensity of extra to dos and fun calendar events.  its so important to give ourselves the gift of the ...
..............👇...............
👉mindful minute👈
...............👆..............
-
the how to: pick one minute in your day where you will stop the mind from racing and turn on the mindful minute.  find something around you that is beautiful ✨, you could even turn on your favorite song to dance 💃🏻 for a minute or like me today i stepped outside into nature🌲. take 3 deep breaths and focus on the beauty within that mindful minute.  naturally the one minute leads to 5 to 10 minutes of positive thinking ... appreciation for something beautiful ... in turn quieting the mind to move through the rest of your day feeling less crazed ❤️ .
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
#mindfulminute #twowordstory #mindfulpractice #shavasana #everyday #anywhere #oneminute #focusonthegood #habits #positivethinking #mindsetiseverything #holidayseason #holidaymadness #wegotthis #levelup #levelupwithalia  #inspo #youknowwhoyouare #needmindfulness #metoo #reminder #bemindful

text: i flew to minnesota for a wonderful but quick visit with friends and family this week. today on my way home i had such a horrible experience i feel it needs to be shared. i arrived at the msp airport tsa with a purse and one shoulder bag. i followed all the rules and went thru the ex ray machine only to be told i needed to be patted down. i endured it but then was told my shoulder bag needed to be opened. the man found my kindle and a 4 oz lavender lotion i just purchased from a craft fair in msp. he made me return it to the trash can and put my kindle in a tub. he demanded i get back in line and go thru the security again. i used some of the expensive lavender lotion and put everything back into tubs. after once again standing in the exray machine they made me go thru yet another pat down. when i complained i had already done this she rudely said i needed to have my hands wiped as well. i failed it because of the lotion and now they put me thru yet another extremely embarrassing pat down and they emptied my purse and my shoulder bag to wipe them down. i was extremely upset to be put thru all of this for no apparent reason. i was treated like a criminal and humiliated in front of other passengers. they put their hands inside my pants, in between my legs, down my shirt and over my breasts three times.they yelled at me when i tried to put my shoes back on and harassed me at every turn. i was made late for my flight and i felt so violated. i was dressed nicely and i did not have much carry on. i say please and thank you and treat everyone nicely. no one deserves to be treated this way at an airport for simply forgetting to pull their kindle and a lotion .5 oz over.  how is this different from me too when i was powerless to their touching me and humiliating me in front of strangers? no person regardless of race, gender or religion deserves to be treated like this. we all deserve some respect. #msptsa #airportharrassment #minnesotaniceisdead #metoo #dontwantoflyagain

text: here’s some motivation for the rest of the week ladies! as i scroll through my old and new followers i’m reminded how dang amazing us women are, like incredibly amazing!! i was raised by strong (ass) women even though their husbands worked they ran the household, my mom was strong in her own way for us. and my sister @danyell_21 is raising her beautiful babies and helping other children at the same time as a nurse. tell me what woman is amazing in your life...if they’re on ig tag them and tell them “you rock!!” i love that i’m a girl mom and i can’t wait to see my girls grow in their dreams and life! #shareyourstory #beachbodycoach #girlmom #momlife #metoo #girlsrock #hustlehard #corporatemom #txmom
name: Jen Castillo
